#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:199
msgid "## /etc/hosts file"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:201
msgid ""
"The `/etc/hosts` file is a static host name mapping table, which follows the "
"following format:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:205
msgid "``` @IP <hostname> [alias] [# comment] ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:207
msgid "Example of `/etc/hosts` file:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:213
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"```\n"
"127.0.0.1 \tlocalhost localhost.localdomain\n"
"::1 \t\tlocalhost localhost.localdomain\n"
"192.168.1.10 \trockstar.rockylinux.lan rockstar\n"
"```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:215
msgid ""
"The `/etc/hosts` file is still used by the system, especially at boot time "
"when the system FQDN is determined."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:218
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! Tip\n"
"    RedHat recommends that at least one line containing the system name be filled in.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:220
msgid ""
"If the **DNS** service (**D**domain **N**ame **S**ervice) is not in place, "
"you must fill in all the names in the hosts file for each of your machines."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:222
msgid ""
"The `/etc/hosts` file contains one line per entry, with the IP address, the "
"FQDN, then the host name (in that order) and a series of aliases (alias1 "
"alias2 ...). The alias is an option."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:224
msgid "## `/etc/nsswitch.conf` file"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:226
msgid ""
"The **NSS** (**N**ame **S**ervice **S**witch) allows configuration files (e."
"g. `/etc/passwd`, `/etc/group`, `/etc/hosts`) to be substituted for one or "
"more centralized databases."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:228
msgid ""
"The `/etc/nsswitch.conf` file is used to configure the name service "
"databases."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:233
msgid "``` passwd: files shadow: files group: files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:236
msgid "hosts: files dns ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:238
msgid ""
"In this case, Linux will first look for a host name match (`hosts:` line) in "
"the `/etc/hosts` file (`files` value) before querying DNS (`dns` value)! "
"This behavior can simply be changed by editing the `/etc/nsswitch.conf` file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:240
msgid ""
"Of course, it is possible to imagine querying an LDAP, MySQL or other server "
"by configuring the name service to respond to system requests for hosts, "
"users, groups, etc."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:242
msgid ""
"The resolution of the name service can be tested with the `getent` command "
"that we will see later in this course."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:244
msgid "## `/etc/resolv.conf` file"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/12-network.md:246
msgid ""
"The `/etc/resolv.conf` file contains the DNS name resolution configuration."
